Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.199 --> 00:00:06.720
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Welcome to Authors and
Wine@Google. We welcome today Randall Grahm.

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:12.110
Just completing a short intro and then Randall
will join us here up front. And thanks to

00:00:12.110 --> 00:00:17.520
everyone for coming. Randall's fascination
with wine began in Southern California when

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:22.920
he stumbled upon a wine shop close to his
parents' house around when we was 20 years

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:23.920
old.

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:29.183
They asked him if he wanted to open a charge
account and he enthusiastically replied, "Yes."

00:00:29.183 --> 00:00:35.720
He realized early on that to be able to experience
the kinds of wines he had there all the time,

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:41.090
he'd have to learn how to make them himself.
Sometime later, he found himself working at

00:00:41.090 --> 00:00:45.870
the Wine Merchant in Beverly Hills sweeping
floors.

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:51.360
Through exceptionally good karma, he was given
the opportunity to taste a large number of

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:59.829
really good French wines. And this experience
turned him into a wine fanatic. He's well-known

00:00:59.829 --> 00:01:06.200
as one of the pioneers of Rhone varietals
in California and he's found success with

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:08.829
obscure Italian varietals as well.

00:01:08.829 --> 00:01:15.510
In 1989, he was indicted into the Who's Who
of Cooking in America by Cooks Magazine for

00:01:15.510 --> 00:01:21.369
"lifetime achievement and leadership and the
improvement and development of American cuisine."

00:01:21.369 --> 00:01:27.600
He was also awarded the honor of Wine and
Spirits Professional of the Year by the James

00:01:27.600 --> 00:01:30.319
Beard Foundation in 1994.

00:01:30.319 --> 00:01:36.259
The 2010 Duboeuf Wine Book of the Year, "Been
Doon So Long," is a collection of Randall's

00:01:36.259 --> 00:01:42.409
writings from the Bonny Doon newsletter as
well as articles, speeches, and essays. It's

00:01:42.409 --> 00:01:49.229
described as a "truly original approach to
the subject of wine. One that's full of wit,

00:01:49.229 --> 00:01:51.209
intelligence, and mischief.

00:01:51.209 --> 00:01:58.130
He takes us through his journey of marketing
and crafting wine. He writes with passion

00:01:58.130 --> 00:02:04.009
about wanting to make honest wines--wines
that represent the places that they come from.

00:02:04.009 --> 00:02:11.540
He embraces the wabi-sabi approach to organic
winemaking as an essential element of the

00:02:11.540 --> 00:02:13.650
beauty of the natural wine.

00:02:13.650 --> 00:02:20.280
He believes that it's through these flaws
that wines become revelatory and capable of

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:26.400
directing our attention to new places and
ideas." Soon, we'll get a taste of this vision

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:33.040
as Bonny Doon releases its first biodynamic
wines in two to three years. Please join me

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:35.520
in welcoming Randall Grahm.

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:37.049
[applause]

00:02:37.049 --> 00:02:47.969
&gt;&gt;Randall Grahm: Typically I begin these séances
with an invocation from Alice Cooper, "welcome

00:02:47.969 --> 00:02:54.400
to my nightmare". [audience chuckles] And
I thought I would give you the Reader's Digest

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:59.650
condensed version of the, or the brief history
of Bonny Doon and then take you up to the

00:02:59.650 --> 00:03:00.650
present time.

00:03:00.650 --> 00:03:08.569
I started Bonny Doon in 1981. Basically, with
the quixotic notion that I was gonna make

00:03:08.569 --> 00:03:14.640
the great American Pinot Noir. This was my
obsession, my idée fix , my mantra. And I

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:20.010
suppose fortunately for me, it didn't quite
work out as according to plan. It was about

00:03:20.010 --> 00:03:25.510
three orders of magnitude more complicated
than I ever imagined it would be.

00:03:25.510 --> 00:03:33.239
So, I, luckily, made the acquaintance of the
Albanian wine merchant, Kermit Lynch, when

00:03:33.239 --> 00:03:41.159
he was a wine merchant in Albany, California.
And Kermit got me interested in Rhone varieties

00:03:41.159 --> 00:03:46.540
and I had a very simplistic hypothesis, which
was: "It's warm and dry in Southern France.

00:03:46.540 --> 00:03:53.530
It's warm and dry in the Central Coast of
California. Maybe the Rhone varieties would

00:03:53.530 --> 00:03:59.670
do well in California." What an interesting
idea. And truly, I mean, we think of Rhone

00:03:59.670 --> 00:04:05.730
varieties as being mainstream, but remember,
30 years ago they didn't really exist.

00:04:05.730 --> 00:04:10.329
There were three Sirah vineyards in California.
All of them uniformly dreadful in their own

00:04:10.329 --> 00:04:11.329
unique way.

00:04:11.329 --> 00:04:12.500
[laughter]

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:16.459
There was Mourvèdre, but nobody knew Mourvèdre
was here because it was traveling under an

00:04:16.459 --> 00:04:24.170
alias of Mataró. And that was thanks to Darrell
Corti in Sacramento who clued me in on that.

00:04:24.170 --> 00:04:30.080
And no one, apart from David Bruce, knew that
Grenache could actually make red wine because

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:35.460
all the Grenache that we experience was fairly
dreadful, drecky, pink wine that was quite

00:04:35.460 --> 00:04:40.170
sweet and quite horrible. But David had actually
made some amazingly--.

00:04:40.170 --> 00:04:48.420
Well, actually made one good one and one bad
one in 1970 and 1971 of Grenache. And this

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:54.820
was in 1984. I was thinking, "You know, this
Pinot Noir thing is not working out quite

00:04:54.820 --> 00:05:00.330
as well as I had hoped. I need a Plan B if
I'm gonna stay in the wine business." Having

00:05:00.330 --> 00:05:03.481
gone to Davis and this is what I decided to
do.

00:05:03.481 --> 00:05:07.590
I'm gonna figure out how to make this work.
So, I needed a Plan B. So, the Plan B was

00:05:07.590 --> 00:05:13.300
let's try Rhone varieties. And maybe let's
try a blend. Maybe if we blended Grenache,

00:05:13.300 --> 00:05:19.630
Sirah, and Mourvèdre together, we could do
something that vaguely approximated a Châteauneuf

00:05:19.630 --> 00:05:21.410
du Pape. [laughter]

00:05:21.410 --> 00:05:29.060
And that's how Cigare Volant was conceived.
And looking back in retrospect, I have to

00:05:29.060 --> 00:05:35.310
say that it's miraculous that the wine came
out as well as it did. There are a million

00:05:35.310 --> 00:05:40.110
ways to go wrong. There's many infinite number
of ways to go wrong. And the fact that I didn't

00:05:40.110 --> 00:05:47.380
go terribly wrong, too often of the time,
is a miracle in retrospect.

00:05:47.380 --> 00:05:59.500
Oddly enough, last year, Bonny Doon--. Bonny
Doon has been this funny journey for me and

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:08.040
last year, last year or two, have been a recapitulation
and reevaluation of where I've been and just

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:15.570
a pause in where is Bonny Doon going in the
next phase? So what's interesting is we actually

00:06:15.570 --> 00:06:20.240
staged two vertical tastings of Cigare Volant.

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:28.630
Twenty-five vintages of Cigare Volant. We
did one in New York at Hearth Restaurant in

00:06:28.630 --> 00:06:36.960
the Village and we did another one at Manresa
Restaurant in Los Carros. And luckily, we

00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:41.390
had some large format bottles and these were,
in many cases, the last large format bottle

00:06:41.390 --> 00:06:42.390
in existence.

00:06:42.390 --> 00:06:48.280
In some cases, they were the last of any bottle
in existence. So, we had all the vintages,

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:54.500
many of them in large format bottles. And
I'll you, this was the freakiest thing that

00:06:54.500 --> 00:06:59.280
happened at the tasting. Many things happened.
These tastings were extravagant. I mean, we

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:04.960
had like literally 12 hundred glasses that
were used in this, that were harmed in this

00:07:04.960 --> 00:07:06.910
[laughter]

00:07:06.910 --> 00:07:14.690
exercise. Of all the wines we tasted, many
of them were very good and some of them were

00:07:14.690 --> 00:07:20.070
not so good. But they were all pretty much
alive. Pretty much every single one of them

00:07:20.070 --> 00:07:22.610
was alive.

00:07:22.610 --> 00:07:29.550
Of all the wines we tasted, the first two
vintages, the 1984 and the 1985 were arguably

00:07:29.550 --> 00:07:34.560
the most interesting wines of the evening.
Not necessarily the best, but the most interesting.

00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:43.041
And so, it really gave me a lot of pause to
reflect. In other words, what the heck have

00:07:43.041 --> 00:07:44.900
I been doing for 30 years?

00:07:44.900 --> 00:07:45.900
[laughter]

00:07:45.900 --> 00:07:50.980
Such that, the first two wines that I made,
knowing absolutely nothing, were the two most

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:58.970
interesting wines of the evening. And it did
make me think that maybe in the earliest days--.

00:07:58.970 --> 00:08:04.520
It made me aware of a couple of possible conclusions
of this, deductions from this.

00:08:04.520 --> 00:08:12.140
One is that logic and ratiocination really
doesn't, is far more cracked up than it should

00:08:12.140 --> 00:08:17.530
be. In other words, thinking things out generally
doesn't always work. Sometimes, you just go

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:22.050
on your instinct and that's a better way.
And certainly in the early days, I was operating

00:08:22.050 --> 00:08:26.390
on my instinct more than any real insight.

00:08:26.390 --> 00:08:31.861
Nobody knew anything about making these varieties.
Nobody knew for example, that Sirah was a

00:08:31.861 --> 00:08:36.690
cool-climate grape. That Sirah actually had
different requirements than Mourvèdre and

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:38.310
different requirements than Grenache.

00:08:38.310 --> 00:08:42.940
The only thing I knew about winemaking was
what I had read in a book, which was "If you

00:08:42.940 --> 00:08:46.380
wanna make a faux Châteauneuf du Pape, or
if you wanna make something that tastes like

00:08:46.380 --> 00:08:49.940
a Châteauneuf du Pape, it needs to have a
lot of Grenache in it.” OK. A lot of Grenache

00:08:49.940 --> 00:08:50.940
in it.

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:59.660
Check. "Needs to go in a large vessel." OK.
Oops. Large vessel. Check. "Keep it away from

00:08:59.660 --> 00:09:06.460
oxygen." OK. Keep it away from oxygen. Check.
And that's what we did. And it worked. So,

00:09:06.460 --> 00:09:15.460
Bonny Doon has been on this funny path for
the last 30 years and the way I characterize

00:09:15.460 --> 00:09:21.990
it is it's essentially been an adventure in
unbridled viticultural id.

00:09:21.990 --> 00:09:28.020
Any etiological id for that matter, too. So
in other words, it's been experimentation.

00:09:28.020 --> 00:09:32.520
It's been messing around. It's been having
fun. It's been trying every possible permutation

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:39.010
and combination of grape variety that one
possibly could. Every winemaking style. And

00:09:39.010 --> 00:09:41.460
having fun.

00:09:41.460 --> 00:09:46.490
And making people happy. It's made a lot of
people happy. The only person it didn't really

00:09:46.490 --> 00:09:54.660
make happy was me, unfortunately. At least
in the last several years. Bonny Doon got

00:09:54.660 --> 00:10:05.040
very complex, very labyrinthine, almost Borgesian
in complexity. Yeah, labyrinthine, [chuckles]

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:07.640
that's a word.

00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:14.070
So, all along the way, I had always and am
always and have always been a lover of European

00:10:14.070 --> 00:10:21.490
wines. And I love European wines for their
uniqueness, their specificity, they're sort

00:10:21.490 --> 00:10:27.620
of about something. This mysterious other
element. And what is this mysterious other

00:10:27.620 --> 00:10:28.620
element?

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:32.590
This mysterious other element is terroir.
It's a sense of place. It's this idea that

00:10:32.590 --> 00:10:40.230
a wine can be not just about the grape, but
somehow also capture a quality of a place.

00:10:40.230 --> 00:10:44.510
And it's not even just the place, but it's
also the culture of the place, the history

00:10:44.510 --> 00:10:47.800
of the place, many, many different aspects.

00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:53.690
And this was what makes great European wine
great. And this is what arguably makes New

00:10:53.690 --> 00:11:02.710
World wines, relatively speaking, somewhat
banal. So, I'd been giving talks and writing

00:11:02.710 --> 00:11:08.840
articles about terroir and how beautiful it
is and how precious it is and how truly, it's

00:11:08.840 --> 00:11:13.440
really the most precious thing that exists
in the wine business.

00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:19.000
And then looking at myself in the mirror and
observing to my chagrin, there was nothing

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:26.290
at all congruent in what I was saying with
what I was doing. Not a single thing. I was

00:11:26.290 --> 00:11:31.610
producing zero Vin de Terroir. Not only was
I not producing any Vin de Terroir, there

00:11:31.610 --> 00:11:35.520
were no imminent prospects for producing Vin
de Terroir.

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:46.400
So, it was time. This was my existential moment.
I had recently turned 50. I had a child. And

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:55.040
I had serious medical problem. So, this was
my intimation of mortality and the thought

00:11:55.040 --> 00:11:59.260
was looking, "Now, what are you doing to do
when you grow up? It's time to settle down,

00:11:59.260 --> 00:12:04.640
buckle down, and try to do something with
your life, Randall, for God's sake."

00:12:04.640 --> 00:12:14.700
So, the first thing I thought is Bonny Doon
is just way too complex. Too many moving parts.

00:12:14.700 --> 00:12:21.720
We were producing, in the heyday, about 450
thousand cases annually, which made us the

00:12:21.720 --> 00:12:27.600
28th largest winery in the United States.
And this meant that we actually had to compete

00:12:27.600 --> 00:12:31.029
with people, who actually knew what they were
doing, who actually really were in the wine

00:12:31.029 --> 00:12:32.920
business and could do all these things.

00:12:32.920 --> 00:12:40.740
So, we accidentally became a large winery.
And we're very leveraged and very, all the

00:12:40.740 --> 00:12:46.490
things that are very dangerous about being
in business. So, the first thought was, "I

00:12:46.490 --> 00:12:50.063
gotta sell Bonny Doon. I just have to do it."
'Cause the problem of course was that nobody

00:12:50.063 --> 00:12:54.210
wanted to buy Bonny Doon for more than like,
six cents.

00:12:54.210 --> 00:13:01.130
So, I ended up selling off those assets that
were semi-detachable. And it turns out, in

00:13:01.130 --> 00:13:06.430
fact, that these were the assets that I least
detached to. So, I sold off our large brands.

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:12.980
I sold off Big House and Cardinal Zin. Shrunk
the production. Simplified the production.

00:13:12.980 --> 00:13:18.240
And then started focusing in on the idea of
finding a place where I could grow grapes

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:28.600
and possibly do something in a true vin de
terroir. So, a couple years go by. It turns

00:13:28.600 --> 00:13:37.390
out that it's really hard to rebrand yourself
when people think you are this goofy, happy-go-lucky,

00:13:37.390 --> 00:13:45.710
anything for a joke kind of winery with funny
labels and this whatever insouciant attitude

00:13:45.710 --> 00:13:48.480
that you have, allegedly insouciant attitude.

00:13:48.480 --> 00:13:56.589
It's hard to get people to take the wine seriously.
So, it has been a bit of a struggle. And we've

00:13:56.589 --> 00:14:01.900
continued to shrink the production. And then
last year, I sold off this other brand we

00:14:01.900 --> 00:14:07.001
had, which was called Pacific Rim. And that
was a wine we had spun off in Washington.

00:14:07.001 --> 00:14:13.250
And all along the way, I'd been like, "How
can I get escape velocity and do this next

00:14:13.250 --> 00:14:21.720
thing?" So, I'd been looking at a lot of property
and going on a lot of realtor dates, if you

00:14:21.720 --> 00:14:30.111
will. And one property's nice and another
property's nice. And I never really was all

00:14:30.111 --> 00:14:33.890
that excited about any of them until this
one property I came too.

00:14:33.890 --> 00:14:38.950
It actually turned out that I had dreamt about
this property. And when I saw it, I said,

00:14:38.950 --> 00:14:44.790
"Hmm. I remember this property. This is quite
amazing." And sure enough, this was the property.

00:14:44.790 --> 00:14:51.150
And it's in San Juan Batista and I ended up
buying it. It gets even stranger 'cause I

00:14:51.150 --> 00:14:56.970
also dreamt about a mountain lion on this
property and I saw the mountain lion recently,

00:14:56.970 --> 00:14:58.670
which was also quite interesting.

00:14:58.670 --> 00:15:03.220
And luckily for me, it was quite far away,
but my colleague, Philippe, got to see it

00:15:03.220 --> 00:15:07.980
at very close range. And that was a little
more challenging for him. About 20 feet away,

00:15:07.980 --> 00:15:15.470
so that scared the heck out of him. Anyways,
so now I've got the property. Now what do

00:15:15.470 --> 00:15:16.680
I do?

00:15:16.680 --> 00:15:24.360
And so, the expressed intention is, how do
you make a vin de terroir? And the problem

00:15:24.360 --> 00:15:32.080
is, how do you do it, essentially, in a short
lifetime or what is left of one's lifetime?

00:15:32.080 --> 00:15:36.800
There's basically two ways of doing it, I
think. Well, there's the European way, which

00:15:36.800 --> 00:15:43.730
is to iterate and observe over 500 to 800
years. This is not a practical way.

00:15:43.730 --> 00:15:45.300
[small laughter]

00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:52.880
It's OK if you can consistently reincarnate
yourself with some degree of precision, it

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:59.370
works. But failing that, less well. So essentially,
I think there's only two ways to approach

00:15:59.370 --> 00:16:09.850
it. One is decide you love X grape. You are
just crazy about X grape and then figure out

00:16:09.850 --> 00:16:13.990
how are you going to make your X grape somewhere.

00:16:13.990 --> 00:16:18.790
In other words, how can you find conditions
that you know or believe will be brilliant

00:16:18.790 --> 00:16:23.100
for this grape? Pinot Noir is a good example.
We've got a lot of people running around who

00:16:23.100 --> 00:16:28.200
are obsessed with Pinot Noir. Most of them
are men. Why? Because it's really, really

00:16:28.200 --> 00:16:29.420
difficult.

00:16:29.420 --> 00:16:35.149
And if you're a guy, you are just genetically
predisposed to do things that are like, pretty

00:16:35.149 --> 00:16:41.840
much impossible because that's how you know
that you're a real guy. So, you got all these

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:51.029
people out chasing this Holy Grail. And the
problem with this, I believe, is that at the

00:16:51.029 --> 00:16:57.540
end of the day, the very best thing you can
do is produce something that tastes vaguely

00:16:57.540 --> 00:16:58.640
Burgundian.

00:16:58.640 --> 00:17:03.800
It will never be as interesting as proper
Burgundy. However, it will be like ten times

00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:08.939
as expensive as proper Burgundy because the
effort that you have to put into replicating

00:17:08.939 --> 00:17:17.039
these conditions is so wildly expensive. And
at the end of the day, I'm not sold that you're

00:17:17.039 --> 00:17:20.749
really gonna come up with anything all that
original.

00:17:20.749 --> 00:17:25.759
So that's one way of doing it. The other way
of doing it, I believe, maybe there's other

00:17:25.759 --> 00:17:32.440
ways, but I haven't thought of them. The other
way is find a piece of property that you imagine,

00:17:32.440 --> 00:17:42.730
rightly or wrongly, possesses the possibility
of expressing terroir. Now, it's a little

00:17:42.730 --> 00:17:43.730
bit tautological.

00:17:43.730 --> 00:17:48.770
What is terroir? Terroir is the sense of place.
OK, well every place then, expresses a sense

00:17:48.770 --> 00:17:59.360
of place by definition. Not all places are
as interesting or as expressive or as eloquent

00:17:59.360 --> 00:18:03.950
as others. Some don't have a lot--. It's like
people. Some people just don't have a lot

00:18:03.950 --> 00:18:04.950
to say.

00:18:04.950 --> 00:18:09.860
Some people have a lot to say. Some terroirs
have a lot to say. Those are the ones that

00:18:09.860 --> 00:18:24.520
are interesting. Terroir is essentially the
ability of a site and a plant to solve each

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:30.070
other’s problems. So in other words, a brilliant
terroir is one that solves the problems more

00:18:30.070 --> 00:18:40.139
elegantly than the other surrounding areas
most of the time, such that it's able to impart

00:18:40.139 --> 00:18:43.230
distinctiveness to that wine.

00:18:43.230 --> 00:18:49.769
And in Europe, it's quite extraordinary where
literally the different terroir, or the different

00:18:49.769 --> 00:18:56.749
cru, or vineyards, are separated sometimes
by 30 feet or 40 feet and they will be very

00:18:56.749 --> 00:19:02.720
different, one from the other. So, this is
really, really extraordinary. So, how can

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:04.899
you get at this?

00:19:04.899 --> 00:19:11.690
How can you illuminate this in a short period
of time? So many of these decisions seemed

00:19:11.690 --> 00:19:16.049
utterly arbitrary. What kind of root stock
do you grow? What kind of variety do you grow?

00:19:16.049 --> 00:19:19.840
What kind of spacing do you grow? What sort
of row orientation do you grow?

00:19:19.840 --> 00:19:28.989
Do you plant them on--? How do you trellis
them? Do you irrigate? Do you not irrigate?

00:19:28.989 --> 00:19:38.270
OK. So, I've had this idea that there's certain
things that need to be observed. So, let me

00:19:38.270 --> 00:19:47.960
get back to what I think is really the gist
of terroir, or the gist of a great wine. The

00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:57.720
gist of a great wine is, I believe, a grape
variety or a blend of grape varieties that

00:19:57.720 --> 00:20:06.659
somehow have a perfect congruency to the site
on which they're grown.

00:20:06.659 --> 00:20:11.359
So in other words, Pinot noir is a brilliant
grape, but it's not a brilliant grape when

00:20:11.359 --> 00:20:14.840
you grow it in Fresno. It's a ridiculous grape
when you grow it in Fresno. But when you grow

00:20:14.840 --> 00:20:22.150
it in Maurice Saint-Denis, or von Romenay,
or Chambretaud, it's totally brilliant. Nebbiolo

00:20:22.150 --> 00:20:29.919
is a brilliant grape when you grow it in Barolo,
not very many other places.

00:20:29.919 --> 00:20:37.429
Cabernet is a pretty good grape when you grow
it in Napa Valley, but it's an extraordinary

00:20:37.429 --> 00:20:45.840
grape when you grow it in the Medoc. So, my
belief is that there's not necessarily--.

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:49.049
There are some grapes that are more interesting
than others. That's for sure.

00:20:49.049 --> 00:20:52.940
And there's some grapes that are not very
interesting at all. But essentially, what

00:20:52.940 --> 00:20:58.109
is interesting about a grape is how well-suited
it is to the place where it's grown. So, the

00:20:58.109 --> 00:21:03.669
real question is how do you find that congruency
between the grape and the place that it's

00:21:03.669 --> 00:21:05.899
grown?

00:21:05.899 --> 00:21:11.230
So, here's how I've broken down the problem.
The first problem is I decided if you wanna

00:21:11.230 --> 00:21:19.070
grow a grape that expresses terroir, you need
to amplify the signal. And it's basically

00:21:19.070 --> 00:21:24.980
kind of a physics or electronics problem.
What you want to do is amplify the signal

00:21:24.980 --> 00:21:26.029
without distorting it.

00:21:26.029 --> 00:21:33.220
So, its signal to noise ratio. So, how do
you boost the signal without distorting it,

00:21:33.220 --> 00:21:42.710
creating noise? One of the ways is not irrigate.
In other words, if you have grape vines that

00:21:42.710 --> 00:21:49.190
are exploring a large volume of soil territory,
they're imprinting on more of the qualities

00:21:49.190 --> 00:21:56.769
of the site and expressing it and distilling
it, if you will, into the wine that's expressed.

00:21:56.769 --> 00:22:03.899
You want to have probably limited production.
So in other words again, this concentration

00:22:03.899 --> 00:22:13.350
effect. Lots of roots, very little fruit.
It's kind of again, concentrating the signal.

00:22:13.350 --> 00:22:16.890
You don't want to deform the wine in the winery.
You don't want to use a lot of new oak.

00:22:16.890 --> 00:22:21.980
You don't want to pick it overripe. You don't
want to use cultured yeast. You don't wanna

00:22:21.980 --> 00:22:30.259
use high-tech methods of reverse osmosis.
All those things, essentially, deform the

00:22:30.259 --> 00:22:38.450
intrinsic character of the wine. So, I came
to this like, "OK, I need to dry farm. I need

00:22:38.450 --> 00:22:39.799
to grow grapes without irrigation.

00:22:39.799 --> 00:22:46.049
I've got this land. It's got really interesting
soil. But you know, it only rains about 16

00:22:46.049 --> 00:22:50.580
inches a year in San Juan Batista." In a good
year, it might be 20, but most of the time,

00:22:50.580 --> 00:22:57.590
it's like 15 or 16, which is pretty marginal.
Some of our soils are nice and deep and hold

00:22:57.590 --> 00:22:58.590
a lot of moisture.

00:22:58.590 --> 00:23:05.789
Others are sandy, not so deep, not a lot of
moisture. I ran into a friend of mine a couple

00:23:05.789 --> 00:23:12.120
of years ago at a barbecue who follows these
things. And I said, "You know, Greg. Do you

00:23:12.120 --> 00:23:18.740
have any ideas about what can I do to really--.
I wanna dry farm. Are there any really clever

00:23:18.740 --> 00:23:25.720
techniques that you know of to enhance the
water holding capacity of the soil?"

00:23:25.720 --> 00:23:29.409
He says, "You know, I've been reading about
this stuff. There's these things in South

00:23:29.409 --> 00:23:33.749
America. There's this stuff called biochar.
And you may wanna just check it out. I don't

00:23:33.749 --> 00:23:37.249
really know very much about it, but a couple
of people who are really interested in it

00:23:37.249 --> 00:23:39.399
and it seems like it has a lot of potential."

00:23:39.399 --> 00:23:45.260
So, I filed this away and a year goes by.
And then I finally got the property and we're

00:23:45.260 --> 00:23:50.100
ready to do something with it. And I remembered.
And I started doing some research on biochar.

00:23:50.100 --> 00:23:57.840
And it turns out that biochar not only is
the answer for producing grapes in a dry climate,

00:23:57.840 --> 00:24:02.899
it's probably the answer for enhancing the
terroir of your site.

00:24:02.899 --> 00:24:08.340
And it's probably also the answer for saving
the planet. So, here's the deal with biochar.

00:24:08.340 --> 00:24:20.100
I go to see the biochar maven, who name is
Hans Peter Schmidt. He's in Bern, Switzerland.

00:24:20.100 --> 00:24:27.250
He's manufacturing biochar. However, so this
is what biochar does. Biochar is essentially

00:24:27.250 --> 00:24:33.409
charcoal that is derived from biomass that
is heated in the absence of oxygen.

00:24:33.409 --> 00:24:41.409
And you get this crumbly charcoal material.
You mix it with very high-quality compost,

00:24:41.409 --> 00:24:49.100
roughly 50/50. You incorporate it into the
soil. And it enhances the water-holding capacity

00:24:49.100 --> 00:24:53.370
of the soil by about 30 percent, which is
coincidentally exactly the amount that I've

00:24:53.370 --> 00:24:58.379
calculated I need to increase mine by to dry
farm.

00:24:58.379 --> 00:25:04.509
But more interestingly than that, the biochar,
the molecular structure, the chemical structure,

00:25:04.509 --> 00:25:10.890
the physical structure has a lot of micropores.
And this creates, and also a really interesting

00:25:10.890 --> 00:25:20.149
carboxyl groups at the ends of the molecules,
and this essentially is like crack-cocaine

00:25:20.149 --> 00:25:23.019
for beneficial soil microbes, for mycorrhizal.

00:25:23.019 --> 00:25:28.989
So, it provides a habitat for them to live
and a nutritional source for them to live.

00:25:28.989 --> 00:25:35.450
So, the mycorrhizal population goes completely
out of control and this is what brings minerals

00:25:35.450 --> 00:25:42.039
into the plant. This is what nourishes the
plant, keeps it healthy, keeps it vital, and

00:25:42.039 --> 00:25:44.810
amplifies terroir.

00:25:44.810 --> 00:25:50.389
So, if you're growing produce, if you're growing
root vegetables, the vitamin content, the

00:25:50.389 --> 00:25:54.749
mineral content, the sugar content of all
these things just goes up enormously. We're

00:25:54.749 --> 00:26:01.769
gonna do, I think this afternoon, a comparative
potato tasting. Of, this is your potatoes

00:26:01.769 --> 00:26:05.279
on biochar, here's your potatoes normale.

