00:26:08.720 --> 00:26:09.879
gonna taste exactly alike,--

00:26:09.879 --> 00:26:10.879
[laughter]

00:26:10.879 --> 00:26:16.320
but we'll find out. We will be the first ones
in Mountain View, California to ever experience

00:26:16.320 --> 00:26:26.220
biochar potatoes. OK, so then it turns out--.
So, Peter is making this biochar and having

00:26:26.220 --> 00:26:32.690
really amazing results. However, it turns
out that only represents a small part of what

00:26:32.690 --> 00:26:33.690
he's doing.

00:26:33.690 --> 00:26:37.600
And it's not even the most interesting thing
that he's doing. The most interesting thing

00:26:37.600 --> 00:26:43.710
that he's doing is he's turning his vineyards
into gardens. And he's developed a set of

00:26:43.710 --> 00:26:53.049
rules for formulizing how do you turn essentially
a farm--. How do you turn a monoculture into

00:26:53.049 --> 00:27:00.649
a polyculture into something that resembles
a state of nature, a balanced ecosystem?

00:27:00.649 --> 00:27:05.149
So, his vineyards don't look like vineyards.
They look like gardens. You've got a row of

00:27:05.149 --> 00:27:09.919
grapes and then interplanted, you've got a
row of apple trees or a row of pears and olives

00:27:09.919 --> 00:27:16.940
and pêche de vigne and rosebushes and flowering
rosemary and sage and lavender and this and

00:27:16.940 --> 00:27:17.940
that.

00:27:17.940 --> 00:27:24.629
And bee hotels, which he calls them. And you
get an immense amount of biodiversity in these

00:27:24.629 --> 00:27:32.070
fields. And therefore, you can produce grapes
with minimal intervention. Switzerland, it

00:27:32.070 --> 00:27:34.440
rains a lot. It's very humid, so they have
to do something.

00:27:34.440 --> 00:27:41.580
But in California, I'm convinced we can pretty
much create an eidetic situation with no need

00:27:41.580 --> 00:27:48.749
to any kind of sprays whatsoever. So, this
is very, very interesting. OK. So, a couple

00:27:48.749 --> 00:27:57.149
of problems solved. How are we doing on time,
by the way? Are we OK? OK, great.

00:27:57.149 --> 00:28:02.369
It still begs the question, what the heck
do you grow? And how do you develop a methodology

00:28:02.369 --> 00:28:08.499
for figuring that out? It came to me. I'm
not sure exactly how it came to me, but it

00:28:08.499 --> 00:28:16.389
came to me. 
Nothing ever comes in one flash. It comes

00:28:16.389 --> 00:28:20.470
in multiple flashes, I guess like sunsets
or LSD or something.

00:28:20.470 --> 00:28:31.619
But I was having dinner at Oliveto Restaurant
not too many months ago. And the owner, he

00:28:31.619 --> 00:28:34.720
says, "Well, can I pour you something?" I
said, "Great. Pour me something wacky, something

00:28:34.720 --> 00:28:39.929
interesting, something fun, tasty, whatever
you think I should have. Pour me a glass."

00:28:39.929 --> 00:28:48.080
He pours me a glass of this stuff. Totally
great. Amazing, mineral, complex, fabulous

00:28:48.080 --> 00:28:53.129
wine. He says, "What do you think it is?"
I said, "I don't know. It reminds me a little

00:28:53.129 --> 00:28:59.009
bit about the wines of Mount Etna--the Nerello
Mascalese from Mount Etna." He said, "Very

00:28:59.009 --> 00:29:03.049
good guess, Randall, but no. It's not Mount
Etna, but very good guess."

00:29:03.049 --> 00:29:10.220
I said, "Well, what the heck is it?" He brings
out the bottle. It turns out it's a wine from

00:29:10.220 --> 00:29:16.679
the Canary Islands, from Lanzarote and the
grape is called Listán Negro. I said, "This

00:29:16.679 --> 00:29:22.710
wine is fantastic." He says, "Let me show
you a picture of these vineyards." He goes

00:29:22.710 --> 00:29:28.549
out in the back, prints off a page from the
website.

00:29:28.549 --> 00:29:33.200
And he shows me a picture of the vineyards
and this looks like the moon if the moon had

00:29:33.200 --> 00:29:37.840
vineyards with palm trees on it. That's what
these vineyards would look like. The vines

00:29:37.840 --> 00:29:45.139
are planted inside of craters and around the
craters are little volcanic rocks, basalt

00:29:45.139 --> 00:29:53.869
rocks, that shelter the craters because it's
very windy, it's very dry, and they need to

00:29:53.869 --> 00:29:58.299
capture every molecule of moisture that lands
anywhere in the vicinity and shelter the vines

00:29:58.299 --> 00:29:59.299
from the wind.

00:29:59.299 --> 00:30:04.549
So, this knocks me out. This has to be like
the most extreme place on the planet where

00:30:04.549 --> 00:30:11.919
grapes are grown. Hot, windy, miserable, terrible.
So, the next day or two days later, I'm having

00:30:11.919 --> 00:30:17.080
dinner with a wine critic from The Chronicle,
Jon Bonné. And I say, "Jon, I had like the

00:30:17.080 --> 00:30:23.549
most amazing wine the other night. This freaky
wine from Lanzarote called Listán Negro."

00:30:23.549 --> 00:30:28.880
And he starts laughing. I say, "Jon, what's
so funny?" He says, "Do you have any idea

00:30:28.880 --> 00:30:33.820
what Listán Negro is?" I said, "It's Listán
Negro." He said, "There's a synonym for Listán

00:30:33.820 --> 00:30:37.690
Negro." I said, "Well, what the heck is it?"
He's all, "You'll never guess what it is."

00:30:37.690 --> 00:30:39.840
"OK, I give up. What is it?"

00:30:39.840 --> 00:30:45.539
It turns out Listán Negro is synonymous with
what is called the Mission Grape. The Mission

00:30:45.539 --> 00:30:52.470
Grape is the first grape that came to California
with the Spanish missionaries. My vineyard

00:30:52.470 --> 00:30:58.690
is on Mission Vineyard Drive, as it turns
out. But here's the kicker.

00:30:58.690 --> 00:31:05.620
The Mission Grape is arguably the worst vinifera
grape that has ever been invented, ever been

00:31:05.620 --> 00:31:08.830
discovered, ever been observed. It has no
redeeming qualities. [audience chuckles lightly]

00:31:08.830 --> 00:31:16.330
It has no color, no flavor, no acid, nothing.
It's horrible. It's totally horrible. However,

00:31:16.330 --> 00:31:21.340
under these conditions, it produces completely
brilliant wine.

00:31:21.340 --> 00:31:29.950
Go figure. What does this mean? What does
this mean? I think it means, again, there's

00:31:29.950 --> 00:31:41.229
no such thing as most brilliant. There is
best-suited. And I think also it means that

00:31:41.229 --> 00:31:47.480
if you have a terroir that is strong enough,
and I strongly believe the terroir on Lanzarote

00:31:47.480 --> 00:31:54.630
is about as strong as it gets, if the terroir
is strong enough the variety itself, or blend

00:31:54.630 --> 00:31:58.059
of varieties, really pales in significance.

00:31:58.059 --> 00:32:02.950
And it really essentially becomes a carrier.
It's just simply a carrier. It's really not

00:32:02.950 --> 00:32:07.049
something that--. You just want to get the
balance more or less right. You want it to

00:32:07.049 --> 00:32:11.649
have the right amount of acidity and the right
amount of sugar. But apart from that, it's

00:32:11.649 --> 00:32:14.940
just there to bring this other character along.

00:32:14.940 --> 00:32:23.259
So, it's really in a sense a question gestalt.
So, instead of focusing on one foreground,

00:32:23.259 --> 00:32:28.609
you flip-flop it so the variety is really
in the background and the terroir is in the

00:32:28.609 --> 00:32:34.960
foreground. So, how can you do that? I think
I may have found a way to do it. You grow

00:32:34.960 --> 00:32:40.739
the grapes from seeds rather than from cuttings.

00:32:40.739 --> 00:32:48.369
And why might this work? For a couple of reasons.
It might not work. I mean, this could be like,

00:32:48.369 --> 00:32:52.879
I've talked to people who know about these
things. Roughly, it's half and half. Half

00:32:52.879 --> 00:32:59.509
the people say, "Randall, this is gonna be
the most expensive waste of time ever." And

00:32:59.509 --> 00:33:02.429
other people say, "You know what?"

00:33:02.429 --> 00:33:08.649
Some variant of, "This is so crazy, it just
might work." Or something like that. Here's

00:33:08.649 --> 00:33:18.879
why I think it might work. One, seeds behave
very different than cuttings. Grapes, whatever

00:33:18.879 --> 00:33:23.369
plant you're growing, whether it's a tree
or a vine, when you grow a grape from a seed

00:33:23.369 --> 00:33:25.129
you have what is called geotropism.

00:33:25.129 --> 00:33:32.619
So, the roots go straight down to China whereas
if you grow grapes from a cutting, they move

00:33:32.619 --> 00:33:39.929
laterally. So, certainly there's gonna be
more of this desire to find water at all costs

00:33:39.929 --> 00:33:46.249
from a seedling. The second thing that I think
is quite interesting is instead of having

00:33:46.249 --> 00:33:55.679
a single variety, or two or three clones,
or two or three varieties, you have essentially

00:33:55.679 --> 00:34:01.879
a true population where every vine is genetically
distinct from every other vine.

00:34:01.879 --> 00:34:09.210
Theoretically, they're all in the same family.
They're all from the same clan, but I'm imagining

00:34:09.210 --> 00:34:16.730
the difference between a full orchestra and
chamber group. Chamber group is lovely, but

00:34:16.730 --> 00:34:22.440
it's small. An orchestra has a depth, a complexity,
a richness of sound that you can't replicate

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:23.440
any other way.

00:34:23.440 --> 00:34:30.210
So, I'm thinking that with this tremendous
diversity, something is gonna happen. Now

00:34:30.210 --> 00:34:36.500
bear in mind, what I'm trying to achieve is
not identify the best grape. Maybe I might

00:34:36.500 --> 00:34:41.159
accidentally find the best grape or find the
best grapes, or certain class of grape that

00:34:41.159 --> 00:34:48.069
seem to be well-suited to the site, but really
what I'm most interested in is what happens

00:34:48.069 --> 00:34:49.220
to a population.

00:34:49.220 --> 00:34:54.250
What can you achieve with a population? And
maybe, within that population, are there criteria

00:34:54.250 --> 00:35:00.809
for inclusion or exclusion, some rules that
you might want to enforce in generation two,

00:35:00.809 --> 00:35:05.170
when you decide, "OK, the grapes that are
the wrong color, we'll put them over here.

00:35:05.170 --> 00:35:08.670
We'll make another wine out of them. Or, the
grapes that ripened too early, we're gonna

00:35:08.670 --> 00:35:15.930
put them over here." But I think, at the very
least, you're bringing something unique into

00:35:15.930 --> 00:35:22.240
the world. At the very least, you're bringing
ten thousand new varieties that didn't exist

00:35:22.240 --> 00:35:23.240
previously.

00:35:23.240 --> 00:35:30.630
So, I think it's a good bet. And whether the
wine's any good or not, I think it's gonna

00:35:30.630 --> 00:35:35.299
be distinctive. I think it's gonna be amazing.
As we often say at Bonny Doon, "What could

