00:38:40.180 --> 00:38:47.200
better than the individual clone. So, taking
that principle--. And again, as long as the

00:38:47.200 --> 00:38:57.900
elements are all coherent, I think that this
diversity will just enrich the wine. Here's

00:38:57.900 --> 00:38:59.770
another way of thinking about it.

00:38:59.770 --> 00:39:06.279
The French make this, I think, really salient
distinction between what they call wines of

00:39:06.279 --> 00:39:13.380
effort and wines of terroir. And a wine of
effort is one that bears the strong stylistic

00:39:13.380 --> 00:39:17.809
imprint of the winemaker, where the winemaker
is really trying to determine as much as he

00:39:17.809 --> 00:39:19.260
possibly can.

00:39:19.260 --> 00:39:23.730
And we do this in the New World. We do this
very successfully in the New World. And it's

00:39:23.730 --> 00:39:29.359
not a totally stupid thing to do. You want
to know. It's like reading a book. You want

00:39:29.359 --> 00:39:33.470
to know how it comes out in the end, so you
wanna know what steps you can take to make

00:39:33.470 --> 00:39:34.740
the wine come out a certain way.

00:39:34.740 --> 00:39:39.420
You want it to taste consistent year after
year. You want it to have a certain flavor

00:39:39.420 --> 00:39:48.359
profile that people like. And this makes a
lot of sense. However, I would argue that

00:39:48.359 --> 00:39:52.680
it may make sense, but ultimately makes a
wine that's completely banal and beside the

00:39:52.680 --> 00:39:53.680
point.

00:39:53.680 --> 00:39:58.609
And essentially, everyone ends up making the
same wine. What has happened lately in the

00:39:58.609 --> 00:40:04.589
last few years is there are certain influential
critics, who will remain nameless, that would

00:40:04.589 --> 00:40:05.589
be Robert Parker--

00:40:05.589 --> 00:40:06.589
[laughter]

00:40:06.589 --> 00:40:14.519
and the Wine Spectator. And people now are
trying to reverse engineer Parker's palate.

00:40:14.519 --> 00:40:21.150
And they're really successful at it. And there's
a company in Sonoma called Enologix , that

00:40:21.150 --> 00:40:29.460
more or less can predict the Parker wine score
before the wine is even finished fermenting

00:40:29.460 --> 00:40:31.460
within a great degree of accuracy.

00:40:31.460 --> 00:40:37.299
So, and they're just out there acting on their
economic interest. If Parker gives it a 94,

00:40:37.299 --> 00:40:41.180
the wine can sell for this dollar amount.
If he gives it a 91, it can sell for this

00:40:41.180 --> 00:40:48.200
dollar amount. So, it's totally rational except
it's evil and bad. And more to the point,

00:40:48.200 --> 00:40:57.460
ultimately, maybe when good triumphs over
evil, people will understand that wines made

00:40:57.460 --> 00:41:04.680
in this fashion have a certain hollowness
to them, a certain simplicity to them.

00:41:04.680 --> 00:41:10.770
They're only as smart as us winemakers and
that's not very smart. A vin de terroir, on

00:41:10.770 --> 00:41:17.730
the other hand, really tries to, forgive the
expression, leverage the complexity of nature,

00:41:17.730 --> 00:41:24.970
or expose the complexity of nature, or reveal.
If you can reveal the complexity of nature,

00:41:24.970 --> 00:41:27.690
it's a much vaster universe.

00:41:27.690 --> 00:41:33.240
It's a much vaster system, a more intelligent
system than the intelligence of a human being.

00:41:33.240 --> 00:41:39.329
And I think, therefore, vin de terroir are
revelatory. There are depths to these wines

00:41:39.329 --> 00:41:43.970
that we cannot fashion through our artifice.
Yeah. Grace.

