like its parent is it? Where do you--?

00:45:15.059 --> 00:45:30.829
&gt;&gt;Randall Grahm: Really good question. Really
good question. It depends on a lot of factors,

00:45:30.829 --> 00:45:36.290
mostly how old the selection is. For example,
Carignan, which is a very old grape, it's

00:45:36.290 --> 00:45:41.299
been around, is genetically very stable, so
the offspring look a lot like the parents.

00:45:41.299 --> 00:45:47.339
Cabernet sauvignon, which is a relative youngun',
the offspring don't look a lot like the parents.

00:45:47.339 --> 00:45:53.369
Now, here's the problem in a nutshell. Well,
I won't be in a nutshell. In a grape shell.

00:45:53.369 --> 00:46:01.309
Here's the problem. It would seem, on the
face of it, that if you like Grenache, as

00:46:01.309 --> 00:46:08.590
I do, the straight forward thing to do would
be to get some Grenache grapes and dissect

00:46:08.590 --> 00:46:10.779
out the seeds and germinate the seeds.

00:46:10.779 --> 00:46:16.910
The problem is that plants are, vinefera plants
are mostly, but not all, 99 percent of them

00:46:16.910 --> 00:46:21.980
are hermaphrodites. So, they have male and
female parts. And it's a little bit like what

00:46:21.980 --> 00:46:28.530
happens in other species when they interbreed.
When a plant interbreeds with itself, there's

00:46:28.530 --> 00:46:30.039
a lot of genetic defects.

00:46:30.039 --> 00:46:36.900
It's like the Hapsburgs with idiocy and hemophilia.
[light laughter from audience] So, with vines

00:46:36.900 --> 00:46:45.579
that are--. A lot of the seeds are not viable.
They're not productive and they grow weakly.

00:46:45.579 --> 00:46:51.450
There's a lot of problems. So, what you really
wanna do is actually hybridize them, rather

00:46:51.450 --> 00:46:58.480
than take the grapes from the seeds themselves,
from the plants themselves.

00:46:58.480 --> 00:47:01.920
Did I answer the question? I'm not sure I
answered it.

00:47:01.920 --> 00:47:06.370
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #4: Yeah, part of it.
But also like, how much variety will there

00:47:06.370 --> 00:47:07.370
be?

00:47:07.370 --> 00:47:10.109
&gt;&gt;Randall Grahm: Oh, so how much variety will
there be? So, yeah. The question is how much--.

00:47:10.109 --> 00:47:16.750
What will the offspring look like relative
to the parents? So, it turns out if you take

00:47:16.750 --> 00:47:23.839
the Grenache seeds from a Grenache vine, it'll
be very Grenache-y. Grenache-ish.

00:47:23.839 --> 00:47:29.890
Certain varieties have more genetic variability.
Pinot noir, for example, if you take the seeds

00:47:29.890 --> 00:47:35.550
from Pinot noir they'll really look weird
and different. Some will be pink. Some will

00:47:35.550 --> 00:47:40.559
be white. Some will be red. Some will be polka-dot.
They won't be polka-dot, but they'll be red,

00:47:40.559 --> 00:47:45.200
white, and pink.

00:47:45.200 --> 00:47:51.269
But in most instances, they'll be less interesting
than the parents. Now, if you hybridize them,

00:47:51.269 --> 00:47:59.039
that's where you get really interesting vines.
And the male part imparts certain characteristics

00:47:59.039 --> 00:48:07.859
and the female part imparts different characteristics.
I'm told, that when you hybridize grape vines,

00:48:07.859 --> 00:48:09.180
it's like a bell curve.

00:48:09.180 --> 00:48:18.089
You get 80 percent kind of look a lot alike
and then ten percent on one side look, are

00:48:18.089 --> 00:48:25.900
really weird and bad, and ten percent on the
other side are really weird and good and different.

00:48:25.900 --> 00:48:30.759
So, you might--. Generally, when you hybridize,
when you're breeding grapes, you’re looking

00:48:30.759 --> 00:48:34.319
for the ten percent that are really interesting
and positive.

00:48:34.319 --> 00:48:37.089
But most of them are gonna look a lot alike.
Yeah.

